ncident, the encounter, the unexpected, the sorrow and the bowl-me-over delight. Bloom speaks to us about how vulnerability, suffering, and the release into joy, can combine as an ongoing, never-ending life practice. She mines her own experience while looking out into the world with awareness, empathy and the willingness to risk being wide open. These poems stand firm with readers. Editor and poet Phil Hall's Introduction "To Lead by Crying" argues for a poetics of empathy, and is an enthusiastic retrospective of Bloom's work. In Ronna Bloom's Afterword, she traces the relevance of photography, psychotherapy, and meditation in her work. Defiant, comical, revealing, impolite yet respectful, A Possible Trust is a retrospective and celebration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetry. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aPoetry. 7aPOETRY / Canadian.2bisacsh  aArs Poetica.  aBuddhism.  aJewish.  aThe Spontaneous Poetry Booth.  aToronto Grief Without Fantasy.  aTruth and Reconciliation.  aWalking the Hospital.  aawareness, therapy, relationships.  agrief.  ahealth care professionals.  ahealth care.  ahospital.  ahumour.  aillness.  aimprovisation.  aloss.  ameditation.  anurses, doctors, social workers, community.  apoetry.  aprescription.  aspirituality.  aspontaneity.  asuffering.  awomen.1 aHall, Phil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112597040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771125970423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771125970/original  a978-3